Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient — one instance, reuse connections
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton so all consumers share the same cache/state
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they bind to their own ViewModel instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | One instance shares state/caching across the app. Holds the `HttpClient` reference. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation gets a clean slate — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Each page instance binds to its own fresh ViewModel. Avoids UI state leaking between navigations. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that manage shared resources or state → **Singleton**. UI-layer objects (pages, ViewModels) that should reset per navigation → **Transient**. Use **Scoped** only if you need a lifetime tied to a specific operation boundary (rare in MAUI, more common in ASP.NET).

> **Note:** For production apps, prefer `IHttpClientFactory` over a raw singleton `HttpClient` — it handles DNS rotation and pooling properly. Register it with `builder.Services.AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()`.
